m -- tAristotle on Music and Theatre (Politics VIII 6. 1340 b 20–1342 b 34; Poetics) -- tNotes on Contributors -- tAcademic Publications of Georgia Xanthakis-Karamanos -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Greek Words 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays, published in honour of Professor Georgia Xanthakis-Karamanos, addresses topics which lie at the forefront of current research on the fields of Greek drama and classical reception studies. It brings together internationally distinguished scholars who provide fresh insights into issues pertaining to the origins of Greek tragedy and comedy, their generic identity, the structure, the morality or the divine and human characters emerging from individual plays, the presence of Greek drama outside Athens in post-classical times, the associations between drama and genres such as epic and oratory or even the reception of Greek drama in operatic works such as Wagner’s Tristan und Isolde. Related art forms, such as music, receive particular attention. Focusing on either broader topics or specific texts, the essays of this volume provide a wide range of theoretical perspectives often combining modern critical trends such as reception studies, narratology or cultural studies with close and acute readings of individual passages. The volume is of particular interest to scholars and students of Greek drama and its reception as well as to anyone interested in Greek culture and its various manifestations.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aGreek dramaxHistory and criticism. 4aComedy. 4aGreek drama. 4aGriechisches Drama. 4aKomödie. 4aRezeption. 4aTragödie. 4areception. 4atragedy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aFountoulakis, Andreas, 